3. Benchmark Methodology

3.1 The Deterministic Benchmark Principle

Theorem: For a deterministic architecture with known cycle counts, power characteristics, and memory latencies, the benchmark results are computable exactly.

Proof:

1. All operations are bounded by FSM state transitions (WCET)
2. Ternary operations have fixed cycle counts (XOR + popcount)
3. Power consumption is linear with active cycles
4. Memory access patterns are static (ROM) or bounded (SRAM)
5. No branching or conditional execution beyond FSM states

Therefore: Simulation = Benchmarking.

3.2 Benchmark Metrics

Metric Measurement Method
Latency FSM cycle count × clock period
Energy Active cycles × power per cycle + idle leakage
Accuracy Derived from tile-specific metrics (included)
Throughput 1 / (latency + context switch)
Power Gating Measured by PMIC rail voltage state

3.3 Test Dataset

The benchmark uses the ST-T1024 Validation Suite (provided in repository):

· 10,000 domain-specific queries (SCIENCE, MATH, PHILOSOPHY, GENERAL)
· 1,000 ambiguous queries (expected to return 0x-AMBIG)
· 500 cross-domain queries (mixed intent)
· 100 edge cases (empty, extremely long, malformed)

